@217   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@218   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@219   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@220   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@221   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@222   = ~Aren't ceremonies for the dead more important for the church of Myrkul?~
@223   = ~What local battles do you celebrate?~
@224   = ~What are the "Feast of Heroes" and the "Song for the Fallen?"~
@225   = ~That's interesting.  It was nice speaking with you, Accalia, but I must be off.  Farewell.~
@226   = ~Sounds like a love-hate relationship.  At least they don't try to kill you *all* the time.~
@227   = ~What's this?  New face in town, eh?  Well met, stranger.  The name is Hrothgar, originally of Hillsfar, but now, after years of traveling up, down, and under Faerun, I am content to call this town my home.  Who might you be?~ [HROT_01]
@228   = ~Bah!  Some civilized nation should come up here and smash the life out of those impudent barbarians.  How do they expect progress to be made?  By sitting on the tundra and beating on a stupid drum?~
@229   = ~Well then, welcome to Easthaven, <CHARNAME>.  Whatever your business in these parts might be, I would offer you this small piece of advice: while you're in my town you'd do well to be on your best behavior.  These folk are under my protection, and anyone who would seek to do harm to them in any way shall answer to me.~
@230   = ~I suppose it is their nature to see the immigrants as a threat to their way of life.  The tribes' anger is probably more out of cultural isolation than any actual threat.~
@231   = ~Well met, friend.  And welcome to my home.  Make yourselves comfortable, but try not to break anything.  Many of these curiosities that you see lying about have... sentimental value.~ [HROT_04]
@232   = ~Ah, they're all remembrances of my adventuring days, little trinkets and the like that I picked up here and there.  More keepsakes than valuables really, leftovers from my days of fortune and glory.  ~ [HROT_05]
@233   = ~I suppose it is their nature to see the immigrants as a threat to their way of life.  The tribes' anger is probably more out of cultural isolation than any actual threat.~
@234   = ~Semi retired, actually.  This region is still untamed and fraught with many dangers.  I've had plenty of opportunities in the last few years to take up my sword and shield and do battle with those who threaten the safety of Easthaven and its neighbors.  In fact, I'm planning such an expedition right now.  That is what I wanted to speak to you about.~
@235   = ~Oh I've seen my share of fortune as well, rest assured.  I've beheld more treasure than most kings, I'd wager.  But it wasn't for coins that I fought and bled all those years.  It was for something grander, more powerful than mere riches.  Adventuring is something that is in your blood, not in your purse.~
@236   = ~And well they should.  You people treat this land like garbage!  Why, this very temple is an affront to the pristine beauty of the Spine of the World.~
@237   = ~You said "us immigrants."  Where are you from?~
@238   = ~Brother Gus~
@239   = ~Indeed?  Well then, this might interest you.  I'm putting together an expedition of sorts, one which would surely provide opportunities for both fortune *and* glory.  This is the business I wished to speak to you about.~ [HROT_10]
@240   = ~We've received word from Kuldahar, our neighbors to the south, that evil forces are stirring nearby in the Spine of the World Mountains.  I am organizing and leading a party from Easthaven south to Kuldahar Valley to investigate.  You look to be capable enough, perhaps you would like to join us.  What say you?~
@241   = ~Don't really know.  The messenger wasn't too specific.  I suppose if you want more details you could ask old Everard over at the temple, but time's a-wasting.  We need to get this expedition moving before the snows seal off the pass to Kuldahar.  What's it going to be?  You in or out?~
@242   = ~This seems to be a dangerous place to live.  I must be going now.  Farewell.~
@243   = ~Hold a moment - just, just hear me out.  Now I've already managed to rally together a few swords for this expedition, but I fear our numbers may not be great enough for the task at hand.  I figure that you might tip the balance in our favor.~ [HROT_15]
@244   = ~Well, as you wish.  Can't say I'm not disappointed, though.  I took you for the adventuring type.  Oh well, I suppose you'll make great fishermen, seeing as how that's the only *safe* occupation around these parts.~ [HROT_16]
@245   = ~I agree.  Even if we don't like the fact that it's happening, conflict is pretty inevitable in life.~
@246   = ~Excellent!  Glad to have you onboard.  I plan to assemble the rest of the expedition and set out for Kuldahar within a few days.  With storms brewing in the mountains, I'd rather we depart sooner, but there are matters that require my attention here about town. ~
@247   = ~What a joke.  I can't believe you're actually serious.  War isn't vital to our existence.  How about things like love and tolerance?  How do those fit into Tempus' plan?  Some theory you got there.~
@248   = ~Back again I see.  Have you reconsidered my offer to join the expedition?~ [HROT_19]
@249   = ~Ho there, friend.  Everything is nearly in order.  We shall be departing for Kuldahar soon.  I suggest you get that supply list over to Pomab before he starts whining.  Testy little fellow, that one.~ [HROT_20]
@250   = ~That's something to think about.  I must be going now.  Farewell.~
@251   = ~There you are!  All is set.  The others are assembling as we speak.  Are you ready to leave as well?~ [HROT_21]
@252   = ~Make haste!  I spotted heavy clouds hanging over the mountains this morning.  I suspect snow will fall in the passes earlier than normal this season.~ [HROT_22]
@253   = ~Hmm.  That seems like a rather empty philosophy.  I'd much rather belong to a religion that stands for something of moral significance.~
@254   = ~You do have a point.  I suppose I do practice what you preach.  The battle between good and evil is as old as Abeir-Toril itself.  However, I cannot revere conflict itself.  Even if I rely on war to accomplish my goals, I certainly do not cherish the activity.~
@255   = ~A spirited one, eh?  I like that.  Well, whatever your business in these parts might be, I would offer you this small piece of advice: while you're in my town you'd do well to be on your best behavior.  These folk are under my protection, and anyone who would seek to do harm to them in any way shall answer to me.~
@256   = ~That said, I'll let you get back to your cups.  I'm sure you've had a long journey, and you'll find there's no better way to shake off the cold of the road than by downing a few mugs of Grisella's best.  If you're in need of lodging, I would recommend talking to Quimby over at the Snowdrift Inn over on the east side of town.  Once you've had a chance to rest up and get your bearings, come by and see me at my house.  It's just a couple doors west of here.  There's some business I would discuss with you.  Farewell.~
@257   = ~Please.  Stay here and relax a while.  I wish I could join you, but there are things that require my attention presently.  Come by my house later and we shall talk.  Farewell.~ [HROT_28]
@258   = ~Ouch.  I guess those barbarians really don't like the immigrants too much.~
@259   = ~What's Everard like?~
@260   = ~Actually, now that I think about it, maybe you can help.  Pomab, the local shopkeeper, has recently expressed concern over the rapidly thinning stock of his store.  He's been complaining that the regular caravan from Caer-Dinival is long overdue, and that if they don't arrive soon, he's sure to be out of business.  Normally, I take Pomab's whining with a grain of salt, but with heavy snows on the way, it'd be best to make sure that caravan makes it through.~
@261   = ~You may not enter the store at this time.~
@262   = ~Interesting.  Farewell.~
@263   = ~I see.  What local battles do you celebrate?~
@264   = ~How pathetic.  Holding a celebration for those who have thrown away their lives...that's just stupid.~
@265   = ~Thanks for the information.  Farewell.~
@266   = ~How about the Feast of Heroes and Song for the Fallen?~
