@562   = ~Hmph!  I am Pomab Ak'azmhir, Royal Diplomatic Envoy of Calimshan and Appointed Overseer of the Northern Caravan Routes!~
@563   = ~And I would like to see some coin before I go to the trouble of showing you my wares.  I have no patience for those who are "just browsing."  ~
@564   = ~[SAREVOK 1] You are indeed family.  No other could have lived to oppose me in person.  Of course, it will not matter in the end.  Ultimately I will prevail, and a new era will be born unto the Realms.~ [SAREV01]
@565   = ~Your poor attempt at sarcasm is an obvious sign of your lowly birth.  I'll have you know that I am third cousin to the Pasha himself!  Not to mention a royal courtier in good standing.~
@566   = ~The Pasha... uh... asked me to accept this post of Overseer of the Northern Caravan Routes, as a personal favor.~
@567   = ~I would not expect someone of *your* station to understand such matters.  Now, if you do not mind... buy something or leave!~
@568   = ~Yes, well... where I am from, one would normally be beaten for such insolence.  Be thankful that I am merciful man.  Now, what can I do for you?~
@569   = ~Well... I... er...  I grow tired of your ridiculous questions!  I have many obligations to tend to, so I suggest you quit wasting my time.  Either buy something or get out!~
@570   = ~What is this?  More barbarians come to my shop?  No doubt with nothing to barter with but more wolf pelts and polished stones.  Very well... let us get this over with.  What do you want?~
@571   = ~Very well give it here.  I do not remember signing you up for the expedition, though.  As the official financier of the expedition, the decision of who goes and who stays will be up to me, not that oaf Hrothgar.  Do you understand?~
@572   = ~You lost the supply list?  Well, I suggest you go and find it.  I cannot afford to have such incompetents on my expedition.  As the official leader and chief financier of the expedition, the decision of who goes and who stays will be up to me, not that oaf Hrothgar.  Do you understand?~
@573   = ~You again.  Why must you continuously pester me?  I have much to do and little time to trifle with the likes of you.~
@574   = ~~
@575   = ~Here they are now:  Feldepost's thugs.  Strike when I tell you to.~
@576   = ~Very well, give it here.  Now, be on your way.  The expedition will be departing shortly.  It would be a shame if they left without you.~
@577   = ~Barbarians?  I think you're mistaken, friend.~
@578   = ~I'd watch where you wag that tongue of yours, shopkeeper.  All this snow hasn't put me in the best of moods.~
@579   = ~Right.  I'd like to see what you have for sale.~
@580   = ~Keep pushing it... I'll show you just how barbaric I can be.~
@581   = ~Northerners?  I take it you are not from around here.~
@582   = ~Right.  I'd like to see what you have for sale.~
@583   = ~No, but I'm sure you're going to tell me.~
@584   = ~Yes, you are a pompous, little man who runs a little shop in a little town at the arse end of Faerun.~
@585   = ~I don't care who you are... I just want to buy something!~
@586   = ~Forgive me, your lordship.  I had no idea.~
@587   = ~Forgive me, your lordship.  I had no idea.~
@588   = ~Sure... and I'm the King of Mithril Hall.  Ha!~
@589   = ~Oh, I see.  Your appearance as a lowly shopkeeper is just a clever disguise... to throw off any would be assassins.  Am I right?~
@590   = ~There's no need to be rude.  I assure you, I intend to buy.  Now, may I see your wares?~
@591   = ~Look you toad, I have gold and I need supplies.  Are you going to sell to me or not?~
@592   = ~Maybe it would be easier if I cut your greedy little heart out and just take what I want.  What do you think about that?~
@593   = ~If you are in such good standing in Calimshan, then what in the Nine Hells are you doing all the way up here in Icewind Dale?~
@594   = ~I'm thinking maybe your brain has been addled by all this cold weather.  Cabin fever, perhaps?~
@595   = ~SPECIALIST MAGE~
@596   = ~APPEARANCE~
@597   = ~abjurer~
@598   = ~My apologies.  I did not mean to offend.~
@599   = ~Whatever.  Can I just buy something, please?~
@600   = ~I see.  Likely this "post" is naught but a convenient excuse for the Pasha to get rid of a royal pain in his arse.~
@601   = ~Oh, you mean you were banished?~
@602   = ~Interesting.  Tell me "Overseer," did you ever hear of such a post before the Pasha offered it to you?~
@603   = ~Fine.  What do you have for sale?~
@604   = ~As you wish.  Farewell, your Royalness.~
@605   = ~Other than die a horrible, painfully slow death... you can do nothing for me.  Farewell.~
@606   = ~I'd like to see what you have for sale.~
@607   = ~Never mind.  Farewell.~
@608   = ~Fine.  What do you have for sale?~
@609   = ~As you wish.  Farewell, your Royalness.~
@610   = ~Actually, Hrothgar sent me.  I am to deliver this supply list and outfit myself for the expedition to Kuldahar.~
@611   = ~Actually, Hrothgar sent me.  I was supposed to deliver a supply list and outfit myself for the expedition to Kuldahar, but I seem to have misplaced the list.~
@612   = ~I hate to break this to you, but Hrothgar is leading the expedition.  You are just a shopkeeper... and a rude one at that.~
@613   = ~I see.  As the "official financier" of the expedition, will you be coming along with us to Kuldahar?~
@614   = ~Whatever, little man.  Just show me what you have for sale.~
@615   = ~I thought Hrothgar was leading the expedition.  You're just a shopkeeper... and a rude one at that.~
@616   = ~*You're* leading the expedition?  Great.  We're all gonna die.~
@617   = ~Whatever, little man.  Just show me what you have for sale.~
@618   = ~I have come to deliver the supply list from Hrothgar.~
@619   = ~I would like to buy something.~
@620   = ~Sorry to disturb you.  Farewell.~
@621   = ~One moment.  I would like to buy something.~
@622   = ~Whatever, Pomab.  Farewell.~
@623   = ~Hey there, matey.  How are ye... hic... doing?~
@624   = ~Not so good, matey.  Grisella, the barkeep over at the Winter's Cradle, cut me off.  How am I supposed ta git any proper fishing done?~
@625   = ~The barkeep says I be drinkin' too much.  What does she know?  I've only overturned my boat three... well, four times.  Anyway, I need me wine to fish proper-like.~
@626   = ~Well, there's no need ta be mean about it.  It's a real problem for me, you see.  I NEED me wine ta fish.  It's a matter of life and death, matey!~
@627   = ~Ye could go ta Pomab's and fetch me some wine.  Then I could git back ta me fishing.  I would be grateful for it.  I'd go ta git it meself, but two summers past, I got so mad at that pompous Pomab that I threw his sorry behind inta Lac Dinneshere.~
@628   = ~Aye!  Thanks, matey.  Ye can find Pomab's store in the nort-east corner o' town.~
@629   = ~Well, uh... I can give ye a bit o' gold.  And... and, ye can be a member o' the Eternal Brotherhood o' Fishermen!~
@630   = ~Ah!  Ye have a bottle o' wine fer me!  Matey, I am indeed grateful.~
@631   = ~Hey!  I don't want ta see any mean hooligans around here anymore.  I can't believe ye won't even help an old --ack!  I'm dying, dying... need... wine...~
@632   = ~Ah, me matey!  Do ye have me wine yet?~
@633   = ~Well, if it isn't the newest member o' the Eternal Brotherhood o' Fishermen!  Thanks again fer helping me out, matey.  Arrrr!~
@634   = ~I... uh... well.  Hmm.  I never really had it explained ta me that way, matey.  I suppose that does make sense, now that I think about it.  In fact, that be the best advice I've had in a long time.  Thank ye, matey!  Here's a little something for yer help.~
@635   = ~Er... thanks fer the advice, matey, but I don't think I'll be doin' that.  I NEEDS me wine, matey, but I can't break the law ta git it.~
@636   = ~Hi, nice to meet you.  How are you?~
@637   = ~Whew!  Been hittin' the sauce lately, old man?~
@638   = ~I'm doing okay but I really have to be going.  Farewell.~
@639   = ~Er... I dunno.  Just do it without liquor?  Maybe?~
@640   = ~You're breaking my heart, old man.~
@641   = ~Why'd she do that?~
@642   = ~You can't let her pull that.  I suggest you smash in one of her windows at night with a thick cloth and use a fishing rod to snag some choice booze.  I can show you how to tie the line...~
@643   = ~You can't let people walk all over you like that.  I suggest you teach her a lesson... while she's sleeping... if you get my drift.  That'll show the people of this town that they can't just push you around.~
@644   = ~Hmm.  That's too bad.  Well, I gotta go.  Farewell.~
@645   = ~Well, is there anything I can do to support your downward spiral into oblivion?~
@646   = ~Hmm.  Alcohol isn't a solution to your vocational dilemmas.  I suggest you go see a priest about your problems.  Farewell.~
@647   = ~The wine isn't really what you need.  It is just a symbol of your lost youth and your failure to accomplish all that you wanted to in the short span of time that you have in this desolate wasteland, this... this, Easthaven.  The bottle is your prison, a cornucopia of sanguinary delight that represents all of your problems in this world.  Seriously.~
@648   = ~You don't really *need* the wine.  You're just attached to the wine.  You're addicted.  It doesn't help you fish any better.  In fact, it's probably holding you back from being a truly great fisherman and enjoying your "golden years."~
@649   = ~Well, best of luck with that problem.  I have to go now.  Farewell.~
@650   = ~Well, is there anything I can do to support your downward spiral into oblivion?~
@651   = ~Too bad, old man.  You're a withered husk of a man and it's no one's fault but your own.  Farewell.~
@652   = ~Well, best of luck with that problem.  I have to go now.  Farewell.~
@653   = ~Sure.  You seem like a nice old man... in that "drunken fisherman" sort of way...~
@654   = ~Just how grateful are you going to be?~
@655   = ~You mean like this bottle I have with me?~
@656   = ~Hmm.  Doesn't sound like my kind of thing.  Farewell.~
@657   = ~Great.  I'll be back presently.~
@658   = ~Whoa, whoa.  On second thought, I don't think I want to be a part of this.  Sorry.  Farewell.~
@659   = ~Well, in that case, I'll do it.~
@660   = ~Well, in that case... here you go.  I just happened to have some wine with me.~
@661   = ~Why would I want to be an old drunk guy?  See you later, wino.  Farewell.~
@662   = ~Don't drink it all in one place, buddy.  Farewell.~
@663   = ~You better make that last, cap'n.  You're not always going to have strapping adventurers around to get you your "medicine."  Farewell.~
@664   = ~It's all in a day's work for heroic adventuring types.  Farewell.~
@665   = ~You reap what you sow, old man.  I hope you wither up and die, you salty bastard.  Farewell.~
@666   = ~Fine, fine.  Here's your stupid wine.~
@667   = ~Oh, alright.  I'll go get your wine for you.~
@668   = ~Listen, you old drunk, I've got places to go and things to do.  I'll fetch your booze when I feel like getting around to it.  Farewell.~
@669   = ~I changed my mind.  I'm not getting you the wine.~
@670   = ~I'm working on it.  These things take time.  Farewell.~
@671   = ~I'm glad I could help.  Farewell.~
@672   = ~Well, is there anything I can do to support your downward spiral into oblivion?~
@673   = ~The wine isn't really what you need.  It is just a symbol of your lost youth and your failure to accomplish all that you wanted to in the short span of time that you have in this desolate wasteland, this... this, "Easthaven."  The bottle is your prison, a fountain of sanguinary delight that represents all of your problems in this world.  Seriously.~
@674   = ~You don't really NEED the wine.  You're just attached to the wine.  You're addicted.  It doesn't help you fish any better.  In fact, it's probably holding you back from being a truly great fisherman and enjoying your "golden years."~
@675   = ~Well, best of luck with that problem.  Sorry, but I can't help you.  I have to go now.  Farewell.~
@676   = ~Well met!  Why, ye seem to me like a fresh new vein of ore, all untried and untested.  I be Hildreth, should ye wish to know.~
@677   = ~Hello again. ~
@678   = ~Do ye not have yer head screwed on straight?  I AM a female, friend.~
@679   = ~What I'm saying is that ye look a little new at this adventuring thing.  No offense intended, we all have to start somewheres.  If ye be looking for tips, I even have some news that might prove interesting to ye.~
@680   = ~What, do I nay look like a wo... oh.  I see what it is now.  Dwarven women have beards, friend.~
@681   = ~I'm not all eyes and ears here.  Mostly I've been keeping to my cups to keep the chill away.  But I have heard that a local sword named Hrothgar is putting together some sort of expedition.  Sounds like it might be fun.  I'll be goin' along meself.~
@682   = ~The folks 'round here say that Hrothgar be a valiant man, but not the type to go dashing off to his death.  They say he be an excellent leader.  We're headed up to the mountains to investigate some sort of disturbance up there.  Ye'd best be talkin' to Hrothgar himself to hear the full story.~
@683   = ~A vein of ore? What do you mean?~
@684   = ~Hildreth? Isn't that sort of a feminine name for a burly dwarf warrior?~
@685   = ~Nice meeting you, Hildreth.  Now if you don't mind... we're rather busy.  Farewell.~
@686   = ~I was wondering if you'd heard any news hereabouts.  Do you think you could help me out?~
@687   = ~Nice to see you again.  Now if you'll excuse me... Farewell.~
@688   = ~But... you have a beard.~
@689   = ~Yeah, sure you are.~
@690   = ~Uh... I see.  I think I'll be leaving.  Farewell.~
@691   = ~Oh, I see.  What news do you have?~
@692   = ~Well, I guess I understand what you're saying. I might come back later for the news.  Farewell.~
@693   = ~Ah, that makes sense.  Say, have you heard any news from around here lately?~
@694   = ~So you're a Dwarven woman?  Oh, well that explains things.  Farewell.~
@695   = ~That's disgusting.  Farewell.~
@696   = ~Oh? What do you know about the expedition?~
@697   = ~Interesting.  Thanks for the tip.  Farewell.~
@698   = ~That's a good idea.  I'll go find him now.  Farewell.~
@699   = ~Well, if you're going it must be a good trip.  You seem like a seasoned adventurer.  Farewell for now.~
@700   = ~Greetings, traveler!  The name's Quimby, and I welcome you to my inn!~
@701   = ~I welcome you back to my humble inn, traveler!  How may Quimby be of assistance?~
@702   = ~Ah!  Enthusiastic!  Yes!  It is rare that I get any travelers at this time of year.  Thus, I want all of my guests to feel WELCOME!  Ha-HA!~
@703   = ~Actually, yes.  The whole town's been talking about the upcoming expedition into the Spine of the World.  Excitement!~
@704   = ~We do have one!  Ha-HA!  Yes, his name is Erevain something or another.  He is an elf AND an adventurer to boot!~
@705   = ~Well, Hrothgar no doubt will be leading the expedition.  I've heard that Accalia, the initiate at the temple, is going, though I suppose Everard will stay behind to minister to the town.  There's a dwarf named Hildreth who's going along as well, and even Pomab has agreed to go!  Ah, what a grand adventure it will be!~
@706   = ~Well met, Quimby.  You seem rather... enthusiastic.~
@707   = ~Hear anything interesting lately, Quimby?~
@708   = ~I'd like a room, friend.~
@709   = ~Thanks, but I am just passing through.  Farewell.~
@710   = ~Hear any interesting news, Quimby?~
@711   = ~How much does a room cost, Quimby?~
@712   = ~Thanks again Quimby, but I am just passing through.  Farewell.~
@713   = ~Er... okay.  How about a room, Quimby?~
@714   = ~Indeed.  Have you heard any interesting news lately, Quimby?~
@715   = ~Do you get ANY travelers at this time of year?~
@716   = ~Hmm.  Thanks, Quimby, but I must be going.  Farewell.~
@717   = ~I see.  So, about those rooms, Quimby.~
@718   = ~Really?  Tell me more about this expedition.~
@719   = ~Thanks for the information, Quimby.  I must be going.  Farewell.~
@720   = ~Well, if an elf AND adventurer likes the rooms here, who am I to pass up the opportunity?  How much, Quimby?~
@721   = ~Did he bring any interesting news with him?~
@722   = ~Interesting.  Farewell, Quimby.~
@723   = ~That's interesting.  How about a room, Quimby?~
@724   = ~Thanks, Quimby.  I must be going.  Farewell.~
@725   = ~Good day.  I am Churin.  How may I help you?~
@726   = ~Me?  Ah, nothing much.  I manage this warehouse here for the fishmonger, Gaspar.  I get paid a sum to store scrimshaw and emergency food supplies here through the harsh winters.~
@727   = ~Well, most of them fish for Knucklehead Trout in Lac Dinneshere.  It's not a rich living in terms of wealth, but living up here, a man can still lead a very rich life.~
@728   = ~Well, spending as much time as I do here in this stuffy ol' warehouse, I don't get to hear much gossip.  If you really want to know what's going on in these parts, I suggest you buy a few rounds over at the Winter's Cradle tavern.  You'll find that drinking and spinning yarns are two of Easthaven's favorite pastimes.~
@729   = ~Hello again.  Can I help you with something?~
@730   = ~Well met.  I am <CHARNAME>.  What do you do here, Churin?~
@731   = ~Good day to you, Churin.  Have you heard about anything interesting happening in Easthaven lately?~
@732   = ~Oh, no need to help.  I was just passing by.  Farewell.~
@733   = ~Well, that certainly sounds like it would be important in a place like this.  What does the rest of Easthaven do?~
@734   = ~Harsh winters, eh?  Sounds lovely.  Anything interesting happen around town lately?~
@735   = ~An important job, certainly.  I must be off now, Churin.  Farewell.~
@736   = ~I see.  Have you heard anything interesting around town lately?~
@737   = ~Interesting.  Thanks for the information.  Farewell.~
@738   = ~Interesting.  Tell me, what do you do for a living, Churin?~
@739   = ~The tavern eh?  Alright, I'll try my luck there.  Farewell.~
@740   = ~Have you heard any interesting news lately, Churin?~
@741   = ~What do you do for a living, Churin?~
@742   = ~No, Churin, but thanks for the offer.  Farewell.~
@743   = ~I hear tell that a fellow over in Bryn Shander taught a tundra yeti to talk.  Isn't that something?~
@744   = ~I've heard that some of the caravans headed south over the Spine of the World have been attacked lately.  Some say it isn't bandits neither, if you get my meaning.~
@745   = ~Snowfall in the Spine of the World Mountains is particularly heavy this year.  If it keeps up, the passes will be sealed for months.~
@746   = ~Strange lights have been flickering and flashing in the temple lately.  At least that's what Old Jed would have you believe.  More than likely it's the booze that's making the lights dance in front of his eyes.  He just happens to be looking at the temple when it kicks in.~
@747   = ~That bitter old man Apsel the Scrimshander said that he saw goblins in the south woods last tenday.  He may THINK he saw goblins, but his vision's only worth anything when he's a finger's breadth away from a piece of Knucklehead.~
@748   = ~The town hero, Hrothgar, has been talking about forming an expedition into the mountains near Kuldahar.  There's something strange going on up there, supposedly.~
@749   = ~Welcome, traveler. May I be of service to you?~
@750   = ~A stranger clad in woodland garb staggered into town the other night and collapsed on the doorstep over at the temple.  They say he was poisoned.  His face was all purple and blue, and his tongue had swelled up so's that he eventually choked to death on it.  Not a pleasant way to go, if you ask me.~
@751   = ~I hear tell that a fellow over in Bryn Shander taught a tundra yeti to talk.  Ain't that something?~
@752   = ~I've heard that some of the caravans headed south over the Spine of the World have been attacked lately.  Some say that it ain't bandits neither, if you get my meaning.~
@753   = ~Snowfall in the Spine of the World Mountains is particularly heavy this year.  If it keeps up, the passes will be sealed for months.~
