@1519  = ~[no text]~
@1520  = ~Very well, I shall leave. Farewell.~
@1521  = ~That is a private matter that I choose not to discuss with strangers. I do not pry into your private affairs, so I will thank you not to pry into mine. Now, if you are done with your questions I would appreciate being left to my devotions.~
@1522  = ~[no text]~
@1523  = ~Very well, I shall leave. Farewell.~
@1524  = ~Hmm... I am somewhat familiar with Auril. The Frostmaiden is not very popular among most peoples. Many worship her out of fear rather than love or devotion. Her truly faithful are rare and secretive, to say the least. Why do you seek such a person?~
@1525  = ~I have questions regarding the faith.~
@1526  = ~I must speak to her about a matter of some importance.~
@1527  = ~Let us end this game, Lysan. I recognize you as the barmaid from Kuldahar. What is a barmaid doing here unless she is more than she seems?~
@1528  = ~It is of little importance. Never mind and farewell.~
@1529  = ~I see... Well, I wish you well in your search. Now, please leave me to my devotions.~
@1530  = ~[no text]~
@1531  = ~[no text]~
@1532  = ~Really? Hmm... I must admit that I am bursting with curiosity. I can't imagine what is so important that you would seek out a follower of Auril... Would you care to enlighten me?~
@1533  = ~It is a private matter that I can only discuss with the priestess.~
@1534  = ~[no text]~
@1535  = ~Not at this time. Farewell.~
@1536  = ~I see... Very well, let us end this charade. I am Lysan, servant of Auril. You have found your priestess. Now, state your business with me...~
@1537  = ~I would first know the tenets of your faith.~
@1538  = ~Followers of Auril believe that all fires should be extinguished, correct?~
@1539  = ~I have come on behalf of the spirit of the tomb here. He is worried about your intentions toward his resting place.~
@1540  = ~My business is to kill you. Prepare to die.~
@1541  = ~I will discuss it with you another time. Farewell.~
@1542  = ~I see... I wondered if you would recognize me since our meeting was so brief. Very well, let us drop the charade. I am Lysan, servant of Auril. You have found your priestess. Now state your business with me...~
@1543  = ~[no text]~
@1544  = ~[no text]~
@1545  = ~[no text]~
@1546  = ~[no text]~
@1547  = ~Auril is the Frostmaiden, the cold breath of the north. She asks that her followers extinguish all flames, open structures to the cold, and to embrace winter... Those are the basic precepts of the faith. I will reveal nothing more to a non-believer. So tell me, why do you ask?~
@1548  = ~Another told me of your faith. I needed to be sure he was not trying to deceive me.~
@1549  = ~[no text]~
@1550  = ~I just wanted to be sure I was killing you for the right reason. Prepare to die!~
@1551  = ~Oh? Who dares to speak of Auril? I would know who this person is!~
@1552  = ~Kresselack, the spirit of the tomb here. He is worried about your intentions toward his resting place.~
@1553  = ~That is of no consequence. What matters is that you sound like the threat he says you are. Prepare to die!~
@1554  = ~Never mind, we will speak of this at another time. Farewell.~
@1555  = ~Hmm. I know nothing of any spirit, but I am familiar with the tomb you speak of. It is an abomination in the eyes of the goddess. I intend to make it more... pleasing to Her tastes.~
@1556  = ~There is a spirit bound to that tomb. He does not wish to spend eternity in the cold and dark.~
@1557  = ~And what of Kuldahar? How do you view it?~
@1558  = ~Enough of this, I am leaving. Farewell.~
@1559  = ~I could care less what this spirit wants. He is dead, is he not? What do the dead care for light or dark, cold or warmth? They are beyond such mortal concerns. ~
@1560  = ~Be that as it may, this spirit cares. He has asked me to speak with you on his behalf.~
@1561  = ~What about the people of Kuldahar? They are not dead, nor are they beyond mortal concerns. Would you deny them the warmth and protection of the great tree?~
@1562  = ~Enough of this useless chatter. You seem unwilling to listen to reason. Prepare to die!~
@1563  = ~[no text]~
@1564  = ~I care not for this spirit or his desires! I have worked for months to rid that tomb of the undead within it so that I can perform the will of the goddess. I am not about to forsake the task now!~
@1565  = ~What have you done, Lysan?~
@1566  = ~Then I shall have to kill you. Prepare to die!~
@1567  = ~[no text]~
@1568  = ~First, I cursed the Vale and the spirits of the dead within it. I bid them to rise and haunt the land. Next, I insinuated myself into Kuldahar society and became a barmaid at the local tavern. From there, I began to spread rumors of the evil brewing within the Vale and the danger it posed to all. It was only a matter of time until someone was sent to deal with the situation. It happened to be you.~
@1569  = ~You cursed the entire Vale? You hardly seem powerful enough for that.~
@1570  = ~All that manipulating of people's lives just so you can destroy a tomb? That is sick.~
@1571  = ~I think I have heard enough. Prepare to die!~
@1572  = ~[no text]~
@1573  = ~Hold your insults, fool! You have no concept of whom you are dealing with. When I cast my curse I felt a calling, a force that I had never felt before. It engulfed me, fueled my desire, and brought it into being! It had to be the will of the goddess herself made manifest in me. I was chosen to perform this great work!~
@1574  = ~And what of Kuldahar, Lysan.~
@1575  = ~A calling? Sounds like the raving of a diseased mind to me.~
@1576  = ~I have heard enough. Prepare to die!~
@1577  = ~[no text]~
@1578  = ~Kuldahar, the great tree, and the circle of warmth are an abomination in the eyes of Auril. Kuldahar shall embrace the winter in Her name or perish in the cold wastes! The will of Auril shall be done.~
@1579  = ~I cannot allow that to happen, Lysan.~
@1580  = ~[no text]~
@1581  = ~Oh really? How sad. I shall have to kill you then. Prepare to meet your fate, fool!~
@1582  = ~So be it!~
@1583  = ~How dare you! I am the chosen of Auril and you shall feel Her wrath. Die, fool!~
@1584  = ~[no text]~
@1585  = ~[SAREVOK 12] Face me!  Face the new LORD OF MURDER!~ [SAREV12]
@1586  = ~Cat~
@1587  = ~No, I think not. I have revealed myself to you and cannot allow you to leave this cave alive. Prepare to meet your fate, fool!~
