@25390 = ~This lighthouse does not appear to be of barbarian construction.  It seems to have been abandoned.~
@25391 = ~Large piles of rocks form the cairns of fallen warriors.~
@25392 = ~The snow on this altar helps to conceal the faded bloodstains that decorate its grey surface.~
@25393 = ~This barbarian ship appears to have been burned in tribute to a great warrior.~
@25394 = ~This primitive sculpture illustrates the ferocious head and long, sharp teeth of a particularly nasty goblin.~
@25395 = ~The head and claws of a monstrous sculpture are covered by mold and wax as it watches over a collection of burial offerings.~
@25396 = ~The well sculpted head and talons of a dragon hold watch over this frozen tomb.  The area is covered with a layer of rime.~
@25397 = ~This sculpture of an orc head is characteristic of northern barbarians' tendency to exaggerate foes and heroes in their art.~
@25398 = ~The side of this vessel appears to have been torn out before being deposited here.  Claw marks are evident upon the remains.~
@25399 = ~You there, halt!  ~
@25400 = ~I beg your pardon, but I do not recall giving you leave to enter my home.  I suggest you leave here at once, or I shall be forced to call down my husband to deal with you.~
@25401 = ~Yes, well... it's bad enough that we must live amongst the filth and squalor of this miserable place.  I will not tolerate having my carpets muddied by the boots of every piece of riffraff that wanders through town.~
@25402 = ~Hardly.  Only the occasional boorish tradesmen that shuffle in to beg my husband for business.  Although we did have one guest stay with us several nights ago.  Queer fellow, that one.~
@25403 = ~I couldn't say.  I hardly spoke more than two words to him.  Baldemar ushered him up to his private study the moment he arrived.  The two of them were up all night talking, and then he was off the next morning.~
@25404 = ~He was a southern gentleman, I believe.  He was rather tall and fairly handsome.  I remember he wore a patch over one eye.  Yes... it didn't suit him at all.  It made him seem somewhat roguish.~
@25405 = ~You would have to ask my husband about that.  I don't bother to involve myself with Baldemar's petty business schemes.  ~
@25406 = ~Where he always is... upstairs in his study, scribbling in his ridiculous ledgers. ~
@25407 = ~Baldemar is a cartwright by trade.  He made his "fortune" by supplying caravan wagons to the trading costers in the region.  ~
@25408 = ~He doesn't build wagons any longer.  Now that he has been elected to serve as Lonelywood's representative to the council of the Ten-Towns, such menial labor is beneath his station.~
@25409 = ~Very perceptive of you.  I am the hapless victim of an arranged marriage.  I never imagined my life would turn out this way... all alone in this wooden shack, married to a buffoon like Baldemar.~
@25410 = ~Unfortunately, yes.  I'll never forgive my father for marrying me to such a churlish lout.  If he could only see the deplorable conditions I've been forced to endure as the wife of a second rate businessman.~
@25411 = ~You again?  My life is miserable enough without having to deal with the constant irritation of unwelcome guests. ~
@25412 = ~I couldn't say.  I hardly spoke more than two words to him.  Baldemar ushered him up to his private study the moment he arrived.  The two of them were up all night talking, and then he was off the next morning.~
@25413 = ~My apologies, lady.  We did not mean to intrude.~
@25414 = ~Actually, we've come to speak with Baldemar.  Is he your husband?~
@25415 = ~Your husband?~
@25416 = ~Yes... my husband, Baldemar.  I'll never forgive my father for marrying me to such a churlish lout.  If he could only see the deplorable conditions I've been forced to endure as the wife of a second rate businessman.~
@25417 = ~Out of the way, woman.  We're here on urgent business.~
@25418 = ~We were just leaving.  Farewell.~
@25419 = ~I take it you don't get very many guests.~
@25420 = ~You don't sound like you're very happy here.~
@25421 = ~Here's a gold piece for your trouble.  We'll try not to break anything while we have a look around.~
@25422 = ~Then we'll be on our way.  Farewell.~
@25423 = ~Yes, we heard.  He was a representative from the Ten-Towns council, was he not?~
@25424 = ~Tell me about this guest.~
@25425 = ~We met Arden Thurlow, the wife of Baldemar Thurlow.  During our conversation, she mentioned that a one-eyed stranger had stayed with them as a guest for the night.  Apparently, he arrived in town several nights ago to meet with Baldemar.  Arden said her husband and the one-eyed man spent the entire night in Baldemar's private study discussing business.~
@25426 = ~We confronted Baldemar about the assassin Wylfdene claimed was sent by the Ten-Towns.  After some prodding, he finally admitted that there had indeed been a secret plot to kill the barbarian leader.  He claimed to have been coerced by other council members into participating in the dastardly scheme.~
@25427 = ~Ice Shard~
@25428 = ~We confronted Baldemar about the assassin Wylfdene claimed was sent by the Ten-Towns.  After some prodding, he finally admitted that there had indeed been a secret plot to kill the barbarian leader.  He claimed to have been coerced by other council members into participating in the dastardly scheme.  We gave him a brief lecture on the virtues of honesty and principle.  He seemed moved by our words and announced his intentions to report the incident to the council.~
@25429 = ~We spoke with the fallen ranger, Emmerich Hawk.  He told us of his encounter in the forest with a great white wolf, and how he believes the Forest Father is punishing him for his shortcomings.  Apparently, he feels that his failure to stop the three brothers in town from over trapping has somehow angered the God of nature. ~
@25430 = ~Emmerich told us that there is a strong possibility that the barbarians have set up camp to the east of Lonelywood, in the rocky foothills of a place called Bremen's Run.  Based on his directions, we should be able to find our way there. ~
@25431 = ~We spoke with Emmerich about Digby's untimely demise.  He seems to believe that Digby was killed by the same great white wolf that attacked him in the forest.~
@25432 = ~We had a conversation with Arden Thurlow, the wife of Baldemar Thurlow, and brought up the subject of the Ten-Towns representative that came to visit Baldemar.  Arden mentioned the man only stayed for one night and spoke only with Baldemar, so she has no idea what they discussed while he was here. ~
@25433 = ~What sort of business is your husband in?~
@25434 = ~I see.  Farewell, then.~
@25435 = ~What did he look like?~
@25436 = ~Do you know what they talked about?~
